HISTORY: 42-year-old female with breast pain.

COMPARISON: 11/14/2011, 11/5/2011, 12/18/2010 and 11/5/2009.

Bilateral digital mammogram performed and iCAD reviewed. There is a
circumscribed mass in the right breast 12:00 position measuring 2.4
cm. The breasts are dense but without a spiculated lesion, cluster of
pleomorphic microcalcification or other finding to suggest malignancy.

BILATERAL BREAST ULTRASOUND

Ultrasound is performed throughout both breasts. In the right breast
12:00 is a 2.8 cm simple cyst corresponding to the mammographic
finding. It is located 3-4cm from the nipple. There are additional
small cysts scattered throughout both breasts. Within the left breast
at the 9:00 position is a small solid nodule 6.5 mm at 9:00 9-10 cm
from nipple. I see little if any posterior acoustic enhancement. This
is probably a small solid nodule.

IMPRESSION:

1. Small solid nodule left breast 9:00. Recommend cyst aspiration with
possible core biopsy.
2. Bilateral multiple benign cysts or a benign finding.

RECOMMENDATION: Ultrasound cyst aspirationof possible core biopsy
left breast 9:00.

BIRADS ASSESSMENT CATEGORY: 3,  Probably benign.

MAMMOGRAPHIC INFORMATION: Mammography does not detect all breast
cancers. Physical examination of the breasts by your physician and
regular monthly breast self-examinations are integral parts of breast
cancer screening. A normal mammogram does not exclude breast cancer if
there is an abnormal finding on physical examination. When clinically
indicated, a biopsy should not be postponed because of a normal
mammogram report.

RIGHT BREAST CYST ASPIRATION

The patient has dominant palpable tense cyst measuring approximately 3
cm, approximately 12 o'clock position right breast. She gave informed
consent and the procedure was performed following usual technique.
Timeout was performed. Appropriate skin entry site was chosen using
ultrasound. Skin was prepped in a sterile manner and skin and
subcutaneous soft tissues infiltrated with 1% lidocaine as local
anesthetic. Single pass made with needle with placement in the
dominant cyst verified ultrasonographically. Fluid aspirated and sent
to laboratory for analysis. The fluid was somewhat turbid and brown.
Likely related to remote hemorrhage. Cyst walls collapse normally. No
irregularity or filling defect. No complications.

IMPRESSION: Dominant tense 12 o'clock right breast cyst has been
aspirated and drained. Needle removed and hemostasis easily achieved.

DIGITALDIAGNOSTIC LEFT MAMMOGRAM WITH CAD

INDICATION: Painful left breast lump, history of breast cysts

Full field digital diagnostic mammography was performed in conjunction
with iCAD. Comparison is made with a recent screening mammogram dated
11/24/2015 and a prior study dated 10/3/2013.

The left breast is radiographically dense which limits the sensitivity
of this exam.  A large nodular opacity is seen adjacent to a
radiopaque marker delineating the area of clinical concern. Ultrasound
will be obtained to further evaluate. No other dominant masses,
spiculated densities, areas of architectural distortion or clustered
microcalcifications suggestive of malignancy are seen.

LEFT BREAST ULTRASOUND

INDICATION: Painful left breast lump, history of breast cysts

The left breast was evaluated in its entirety. At the 5:00 position
there is a cyst measuring 2.1 x 2.1 x 1.8 cm which represents the
palpable abnormality. Edematous changes are seen in the surrounding
breast tissue. There is also an adjacent 0.5 x 0.7 x 0.6 cm cyst. At
the 1:00 position is a cluster of cystic densities measuring 0.6 x 0.4
x 0.2 cm in aggregate. At the 10:00 position there is a 0.4 x 0.5 x
0.2 cm cyst.

IMPRESSION:

1. Large cyst with edematous changes in the adjacent soft tissues
representing the palpable abnormality.
2. Additional smaller cysts are seen as delineated above.

RECOMMENDATION: Annual mammographic followup is advised. Patient has
had breast cysts aspirated in the past. If clinically warranted, this
could also be pursued.

Results of this examination and recommendations were discussed with
the patient.

BI-RADS assessment category: 2-benign
